`crates/ctx-status/src/runner` implements the five task-tracking operations: `migrate`, `add_task`, `delete_task`, `list`, `render`, all backed by a JSON array of tasks persisted through the `Fs` trait (real in production, `FakeFs`/`BTreeMap` in tests).

The store's JSON is the shared contract across every operation: `migrate` seeds it once from a markdown table (sequential ids, source order, refuses to re-run); `add_task` appends with a fresh id past current max, validating impact values; `delete_task` removes by id, preserving insertion order, erroring on unknown ids; `list` deserializes it but backfills missing ids for legacy rows (assigned in store order) while displaying in priority order (high/easy before low/hard); `render` re-syncs the markdown view from the store without mutating it. Any change to the JSON task schema must be checked against all five operations, since each reads or writes the same structure independently rather than through a shared serialization helper.

Editors changing id-assignment logic should note the divergence between storage order (insertion/source order, used for id assignment) and display order (priority-sorted) — conflating them breaks `list`'s backfill invariant.